with investigation. I'm looking at artificial intelligence and thinking, what can it do for me?

22
00:02:09,439 --> 00:02:16,240
Alex asks Alistair to explain where he's coming from. This means explain his perspective or point

23
00:02:16,240 --> 00:02:22,400
of view. In informal English, we'll often ask someone, do you get where I'm coming from?

24
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:26,080
And we're asking whether they understand our opinion or perspective.

25
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:32,159
Alistair explains that he's interested in how artificial intelligence could help solve crimes,

26
00:02:32,159 --> 00:02:37,439
because he's a police officer with a background in investigations. If you have a background in

27
00:02:37,439 --> 00:02:43,280
something, it means most of your previous work or experience was related to something. For example,

28
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:49,520
I work as a producer at BBC Learning English Now Making Programs, but my background is in

29
00:02:49,520 --> 00:02:56,479
classroom teaching. Alistair talks about using artificial intelligence for training and asks,

30
00:02:56,479 --> 00:03:02,719
what can it do for me? This means how can artificial intelligence help or improve something?

31
00:03:02,719 --> 00:03:08,080
When a crime happens, police officers have to collect and review a lot of information to find

32
00:03:08,160 --> 00:03:13,280
evidence. When you have a lot of information to review, it can be difficult to know what's

33
00:03:13,280 --> 00:03:19,680
important and find patterns which might be relevant to the crime. But Professor Roof Morgan,

34
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:26,320
an expert in crime and forensic science, thinks AI could help speed up police work,

35
00:03:26,320 --> 00:03:32,800
as she told BBC Radio 4's The Artificial Human. I think we're seeing a renaissance in the pattern

36
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:37,600
recognition forms of evidence, so finger marks, footwear marks. There's been lots of challenges with

37
00:03:37,599 --> 00:03:41,759
those forms of evidence over the last 10 years, probably go a little bit out of favour. And yet,

38
00:03:41,759 --> 00:03:46,159
what we're beginning to see now with AI is that you can take a photo of a mark with your phone,

39
00:03:46,799 --> 00:03:50,240
compare that mark to the database and get real time insight.

40
00:03:51,039 --> 00:03:56,319
Roof says there's a renaissance in looking at patterns in evidence, such as finger marks or

41
00:03:56,319 --> 00:04:02,719
footwear marks. Renaissance means new interest or activity in a particular topic or area.

42
00:04:02,719 --> 00:04:08,240
This kind of evidence went a little bit out of favour over recent years because of the

43
00:04:08,240 --> 00:04:15,039
excitement around DNA evidence. If something is out of favour, it's less popular or appealing.

44
00:04:15,039 --> 00:04:21,759
But AI could mean that patterns in finger marks or footwear marks are useful in solving crimes again.

45
00:04:22,399 --> 00:04:28,000
This is because AI can be used to compare a picture of a mark with a database of pictures from

46
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:34,720
other crimes and get real time insight. The adjective real time means the information is presented

47
00:04:34,720 --> 00:04:41,839
at the same time that it's happening. Yes, AI can compare lots of information very quickly,

48
00:04:41,839 --> 00:04:47,279
which makes finding patterns in evidence much easier and more reliable.

49
00:04:47,279 --> 00:04:52,480
There are some problems with using AI to solve crimes, though. To find these patterns,

50
00:04:52,480 --> 00:04:57,759
lots of private information would need to be collected. And police usually have to give

51
00:04:57,759 --> 00:05:03,120
clear reasons why they need access to certain information in their investigations.

52
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:08,720
It's unlikely an AI-powered robot would ever replace a detective anytime soon.

53
